Phase 6 was a behavior-preserving physical module move. Phase 8 removes the
legacy shim paths that Phase 6 left behind.

- Root `capture.rs`, `dirs.rs`, and `tree.rs` were removed in Phase 8. Their
  implementations live under `overlay/`.
- Isolated create/wiring, destroy/eviction, persisted recovery, and lease/time
  helper code lives under `lifecycle/`.
- Remount state, report/probe/result types, and remount apply methods live
  under `lifecycle/remount/`.
- Namespace holder control, FD mapping, setns-runner request prep, and cgroup
  creation live under `namespace/`.
- Host and isolated mode surfaces live under `network_mode/`.
- Dedicated-network setup/cleanup internals live under
  `isolated_setup/`. `dns.rs`, `rtnl.rs`, and `netfilter/*` kept their
  mechanism names. The veth/IP-pool manager remains in
  `isolated_setup/mod.rs` because the file is small and further
  splitting would add churn without behavior value in this phase.
- Legacy host and isolated-network source modules were removed in Phase 8 after
  remaining definitions moved into `network_mode/host.rs` and
  `network_mode/isolated.rs`.

## Holder/Setns-Only Execution

Phase 7 makes workspace command execution holder/setns-only.

- Host command workspace creation uses the same runtime-owned base lease and
  overlay dirs as Phase 3, but now launches `ns-holder` with
  `NamespaceNetwork::Host` before handing the command to `CommandOps`.
- Host holders create user, mount, and PID namespaces only. They do not create
  a dedicated network namespace, allocate veth devices, rewrite DNS, or install
  isolated network rules.
- Isolated-network workspace create now passes `NamespaceNetwork::Isolated` explicitly.
  The existing isolated create path still creates user, mount, PID, and network
  namespaces and keeps the existing isolated network setup.
- Host and isolated-network workspace command prep both serialize `RunMode::SetNs`.
  Workspace command requests do not carry a public runner-mode enum.
- Missing holder FDs are command preparation errors. Host requires user, mount,
  and PID FDs. Isolated requires user, mount, PID, and network FDs.
- `FreshNs` remains in `linux-namespace-subprocess::protocol::RunMode` only for
  legacy/non-workspace subprocess compatibility. Phase 7 did not retire the
  enum variant or legacy compatibility paths.
- Phase 8 legacy export/name retirement was implemented after this holder/setns
  slice, without changing holder/setns execution semantics.

